in each country, this book points to common strategies that offer promise for a more dynamic model of unionism is the global North. The editors have also created a companion website for the book, which features literature reviews, full case studies, updates, and links to related publications. Visit it at www.mobilizing-against-inequality.info.Contributors: Lee H. Adler, Cornell University; Gabriella Alberti, Leeds University; Daniel B. Cornfield, Vanderbilt University; Michael Fichter, Global Labour University, Berlin; Janice Fine, Rutgers, The State University of New Jersey; Jane Holgate, Leeds University; Denisse Roca-Servat, Pontifical Bolivarian University, Colombia; Maite Tapia, Michigan State University; Lowell Turner, Cornell University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aForeign workersxLabor unionsxOrganizingvCase studies. 0aLabor movementvCase studies. 0aMinority labor union membersvCase studies. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science.  aimmigrant workers in unions, Germany, France, United Kingdom, United States, immigrant mobilization, social countermovements, immigrant workforces.1 aAdler, Lee H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTapia, Maite, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTurner, Lowell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147024040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470240/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles